Drawn more to lighter subjects, Barnet survived StalinÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢s crackdowns by flying under the radar, and was able to create two genuine masterpieces in the ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢30s, ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œOutskirtsÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½ (1933, available on an Image DVD with his silent comedy ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œThe Girl With the HatboxÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½) and the transcendently beautiful ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã…â€œBy the Bluest of SeasÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã‚ï¿½ (1936, unavailable in the United States although a budget disc is out in France). He continued to work regularly (though seldom at the height of his talent) through the early ÃƒÂ¢Ã¢â€šÂ¬Ã¢â€žÂ¢60s, when he put an end to decades of disappointment by hanging himself in a hotel room.

